[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Adia Harvey Wingfield is Professor of Sociology and a Faculty Fellow in the Office of the Provost at Washington University in St.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Louis, where her research interests are in the persistence of intersectional racial and gender inequalities in professional occupations, in particular the challenges facing black men in workplaces where they are in the minority.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] She attended Spelman College as an undergraduate, studying English.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Wingfield received her M.A. and Ph.D. in sociology from Johns Hopkins University.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] After receiving her Ph.D., she served as an assistant professor of sociology at Hollins University from 2004 to 2006.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] In 2006, she joined the sociology department at Georgia State University, where she served as an assistant professor of sociology until 2012.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] In 2011, she was a visiting professor of sociology at Rikkyo University in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] In 2012, she received tenure and became an associate professor of sociology at Georgia State.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Louis to become one of three professors that re-established the sociology department at Washington University in St.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Louis, along with David Cunningham, Ku Klux Klan scholar and former chair of the sociology department at Brandeis University, and Jake Rosenfeld, scholar on labor and unions and former sociology professor at University of Washington.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] In 2018, Wingfield served as President of Sociologists for Women in Society a national organization that encourages feminist research and teaching in sociology.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] She served as the President of the Southern Sociological Society from 2020 to 2021.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] She is a founding member of the Sociology Action Network Advisory Board and is serving from 2018 to 2020 as a member of the American Sociological Association Program Committee.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Wingfield is a contributing writer for *Harvard Business Review, Slate,* *The Atlantic, Fortune,* and *Inside Higher Ed,* and she has been quoted on NPR and in newspapers such as The New York Times, The Guardian, the Chicago Sun Times, Pacific Standard, and the Christian Science Monitor.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Wingfield analyzed the racial components of the popular sociological term "glass escalator" in her 2009 article, "Racializing the Glass Escalator: Reconsidering Men's Experiences with Women's Work" which she published in the journal, Gender & Society.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Her article is widely cited and acclaimed.
[src:erving-goffman/adia-harvey-wingfield] Harvey, Doctor of Education, was also an academic, and her mother was a K-12 educator.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] Masson argues that psychotherapy is a form of socially sanctioned abuse.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] Masson argues that therapists ask patients to do more than is reasonably possible, they "distort another person's reality" to try to change people in ways that conform to the therapist's concepts and prejudices.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] Therapists are, in Masson's opinion, inevitably corrupted by power and "abuse of one form or another is built into the very fabric of psychotherapy".
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] He gives an example of a therapist who used his "insensitivity, historical bewilderment, and general incomprehension" as "weapons with which he punish [a] woman for not viewing the universe the way he did".
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] He argues that therapists impose an internal understanding of people's problems, refusing to help a patient reach an external understanding of the world citing the example of psychiatry's failure to acknowledge the existence of sexual abuse of children.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] Masson explores Carl Jung's relationship with the Nazi party and argues that the interpretation of dreams by therapists used by Jung could impose an interpretation of their wishes on an individual giving the example of a female patient whose dreams Jung interpreted as a secret desire to marry.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] Of Rogerian psychotherapy, Masson argues that the theory is inconsistent because the therapeutic relationship prevents real connection and therefore the empathy that it claims is necessary for effective therapy, because the therapist is not in any way invested in the relationship.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] He points out that in his later work with committed patients diagnosed with schizophrenia, the patients were compelled to engage in therapy, which is at odds with the principles of client-centered voluntary exploration in therapy.
[src:erving-goffman/against-therapy] He concludes by arguing that therapy has a lack of interest in social injustice, that the training process can act as a form of social indoctrination arguing that psychiatry is fundamentally unreformable.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In the social sciences there is a standing debate over the primacy of **structure or agency** in shaping human behaviour.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] *Structure* is the recurrent patterned arrangements which influence or limit the choices and opportunities available.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] *Agency* is the capacity of individuals to act independently and to make their own free choices.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The structure versus agency debate may be understood as an issue of socialization against autonomy in determining whether an individual acts as a free agent or in a manner dictated by social structure.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Structural functionalists such as Émile Durkheim see structure and hierarchy as essential in establishing the very existence of society.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Theorists such as Karl Marx, by contrast, emphasize that the social structure can act to the detriment of the majority of individuals in a society.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In both these instances "structure" may refer to something both material (or "economic") and cultural (i.e. related to norms, customs, traditions and ideologies).
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Some theorists put forward that what we know as our social existence is largely determined by the overall structure of society.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The perceived agency of individuals can also mostly be explained by the operation of this structure.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] All of these schools in this context can be seen as forms of holism – the notion that "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] On the other hand, other theorists stress the capacity of individual "agents" to construct and reconstruct their worlds.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In this sense the individual can be viewed as more influential than the system.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Lastly, a third option, taken by many modern social theorists, attempts to find a point of balance between the two previous positions.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] They see structure and agency as complementary forces – structure influences human behaviour, and humans are capable of changing the social structures they inhabit.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Structuration issue one prominent example of this view.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The first approach (emphasizing the importance of societal structure) dominated in classical sociology.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Theorists saw unique aspects of the social world that could not be explained simply by the sum of the individuals present.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Durkheim strongly believed that the collective had emergent properties of its own and saw the need for a science which would deal with this emergence.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The second approach (methodological individualism, etc.), however, also has a well-established position in social science.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Many theorists still follow this course (economists, for example, tend to disregard any kind of holism).
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The central debate, therefore, pits theorists committed to the notions of methodological holism against those committed to methodological individualism.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The second notion, methodological individualism, is the idea that actors are the central theoretical and ontological elements in social systems, and social structure is an epiphenomenon, a result and consequence of the actions and activities of interacting individuals.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Georg Simmel (1858–1918) was one of the first generation of German nonpositivist sociologists.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] His studies pioneered the concepts of social structure and agency.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] His most famous works today include *The Metropolis and Mental Life* and *The Philosophy of Money*.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Norbert Elias (1897–1990) was a German sociologist whose work focused on the relationship between power, behaviour, emotion, and knowledge over time.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] He significantly shaped what is called *process sociology* or *figurational sociology*.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Talcott Parsons (1902–1979) was an American sociologist and the main theorist of action theory (misleadingly called "structural functionalism") in sociology from the 1930s in the United States.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] His works analyze social structure but in terms of voluntary action and through patterns of normative institutionalization by codifying its theoretical gestalt into a system-theoretical framework based on the idea of living systems and cybernetic hierarchy.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] For Parsons there is no structure–agency problem.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] His book *Distinction: A Social Critique of the Judgement of Taste* (1979), was named as one of the 20th century's 10 most important works of sociology by the International Sociological Association.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The key concepts in Bourdieu's work are habitus, field, and capital.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The agent is socialized in a "field", an evolving set of roles and relationships in a social domain, where various forms of "capital" such as prestige or financial resources are at stake.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] As the agent accommodates to their roles and relationships in the context of their position in the field, they internalize relationships and expectations for operating in that domain.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] These internalized relationships and habitual expectations and relationships form, over time, the *habitus*.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Bourdieu's work attempts to reconcile structure and agency, as external structures are internalized into the habitus while the actions of the agent externalize interactions between actors into the social relationships in the field.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Bourdieu's theory, therefore, is a dialectic between "externalizing the internal", and "internalizing the external".
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Berger and Thomas Luckmann in their *Social Construction of Reality* (1966) saw the relationship between structure and agency as dialectical.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Society forms the individuals who create society – forming a continuous loop.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The sociologist James Samuel Coleman famously diagramed the link between macrosociological phenomena and individual behaviour in what is commonly referred to as *Coleman's Boat*.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] A macro-level phenomenon is described as instigating particular actions by individuals, which results in a subsequent macro-level phenomenon.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In this way, individual action is taken in reference to a macro-sociological structure, and that action (by many individuals) results in change to that macro-structure.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Contemporary sociology has generally aimed toward a reconciliation of structure and agency as concepts.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Anthony Giddens has developed structuration theory in such works as *The Constitution of Society* (1984).
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] He presents a developed attempt to move beyond the dualism of structure and agency and argues for the "duality of structure" – where social structure is both the medium and the outcome of social action, and agents and structures as mutually constitutive entities with "equal ontological status".
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] For Giddens, an agent's common interaction with structure, as a system of norms, is described as *structuration*.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The term *reflexivity* is used to refer to the ability of an agent to consciously alter his or her place in the social structure; thus globalization and the emergence of the 'post-traditional' society might be said to allow for "greater social reflexivity".
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Social and political sciences are therefore important because social knowledge, as self-knowledge, is potentially emancipatory.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] His access to research on structure and agency is characterized by socialization theory.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Central to the theory is the life-long interaction between the individual and his/her longing for freedom and autonomy, and society with its pressure of order and structure.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] As he states in his "Model of Productive Processing of Reality (PPR)", personality "does not form independently from society any of its functions or dimensions but is continuously being shaped, in a concrete, historically conveyed life world, throughout the entire space of the life span".
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The PPR model places the human subject in a social and ecological context that must be absorbed and processed subjectively.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The human being as an autonomous subject has the lifelong task to harmonize the processes of social integration and personal individualization.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] This task is mastered in specific steps that are typical for the respective age and the achieved developmental stage ("developmental tasks").
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The social theorist and legal philosopher Roberto Mangabeira Unger developed the thesis of negative capability to address this problem of agency in relation to structure.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In his work on false necessity – or anti-necessitarian social theory – Unger recognizes the constraints of structure and its molding influence upon the individual, but at the same time finds the individual able to resist, deny, and transcend their context.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The varieties of this resistance are negative capability.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Unlike other theories of structure and agency, *negative capability* does not reduce the individual to a simple actor possessing only the dual capacity of compliance or rebellion, but rather sees him or her as able to partake in a variety of activities of self empowerment.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] A recent development in the debate is the critical realist structure/agency perspective embodied in Roy Bhaskar's transformational model of social action (TMSA) which he later expanded into his concept of four-planar social being.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] A major difference between Giddens' structuration theory and the TMSA is that the TMSA includes a temporal element (time).
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The TMSA has been further advocated and applied in other social science fields by additional authors, for example in economics by Tony Lawson and in sociology by Margaret Archer.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In 2005, the *Journal of Management Studies* debated the merits of critical realism.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Kenneth Wilkinson in the *Community in Rural America* took an interactional/field theoretical perspective focusing on the role of community agency in contributing to the emergence of community.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] With critical psychology as a framework, the Danish psychologist Ole Dreier proposes in his book *Psychotherapy in Everyday Life* that we may best conceptualize persons as participants in social practices (that constitute social structures) who can either reproduce or change these social practices.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] The structure/agency debate continues to evolve, with contributions such as Nicos Mouzelis's *Sociological Theory: What Went Wrong?* and Margaret Archer's *Realist Social Theory: The Morphogenetic Approach* continuing to push the ongoing development of structure/agency theory.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Work in information systems by Mutch (2010) has emphasized Archer's Realist Social Theory as well as Robert Archer's (2018) application in the field of education policy and organization theory.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] In entrepreneurship a discussion between Sarason et al. and Mole & Mole (2010) used Archer's theory to critique structuration by arguing that starting a new business organization needs to be understood in the context of social structure and agency.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] However, this depends upon one's view of structure, which differs between Giddens and Archer.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Hence if strata in social reality have different ontologies, then they must be viewed as a dualism.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Moreover, agents have causal power, and ultimate concerns which they try to fallibly put into practice.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] Mole and Mole propose entrepreneurship as the study of the interplay between the structures of a society and the agents within it.
[src:erving-goffman/agency-and-structure] George Ritzer examines these issues (and surveys the structure agency debate) in greater detail in his book *Modern Sociological Theory* (2000).
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] Albion Woodbury Small was born in Buckfield, Maine, to parents Reverend Albion Keith Parris Small and Thankful Lincoln Woodbury.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] He lived in Bangor, Maine, and then Portland, Maine, where he attended public schools in both places.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] He attended Colby University, now known as Colby College, from 1872 until he graduated in 1876.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] He studied theology from 1876 to 1879 at the Andover Newton Theological School.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] From 1879 to 1881 he studied at the University of Leipzig and the University of Berlin in Germany history, social economics and politics.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] While in Germany, he married Valeria von Massow in June 1881, with whom he had one child.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] In the fall of 1881, he became chair of history and political economy at Colby College.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] From 1888 to 1889 he studied history at the Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, Maryland, and was promoted in 1889 with a PhD thesis (*The Beginnings of American Nationality*) at the same time continuing to teach at Colby College.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] From 1889 to 1892 he was the 10th president of Colby.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] In 1892 he founded the first department of sociology at the University of Chicago.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] He chaired this department for over 30 years.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] Vincent, published the first textbook in sociology: An introduction to the study of society.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] In 1895 he established the American Journal of Sociology.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] From 1905 to 1925 he served as Dean of the Graduate School of Arts and Literature at the University of Chicago.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] Albion Woodbury Small was a member of the Delta Kappa Epsilon fraternity (Xi chapter).
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] Albion Small can be attributed with many "firsts" in the field of sociology.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] In 1892, he helped to create a department of social science at the University of Chicago, which was the first-ever sociology department in the United States.
[src:erving-goffman/albion-woodbury-small] Then, in 1894, along with colleague George E.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Morris, an African-American and the grandson of sharecroppers, was born in rural Tutwiler, Mississippi.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] As a child he experienced Jim Crow racism and segregation; one of his earliest memories was the lynching of 14-year-old Emmett Till.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] He moved to Chicago with his family, and enrolled at Southeast Community College in 1968.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Morris studied sociology and social movements at Bradley University and the State University of New York, Stony Brook, receiving his PhD in 1980.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Morris was an associate professor of sociology at the University of Michigan from 1980 to 1990.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] He joined the faculty of Northwestern University in 1988, where he was the Leon Forrest professor of sociology and African-American Studies.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Previously at Northwestern, he chaired the sociology department, directed Asian American Studies, served as associate dean for faculty affairs, and served as interim dean for the Weinberg College of Arts and Sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Morris was inspired by the moving oration of Martin Luther King Jr. and the scholarship of sociologist W.E.B.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Du Bois, the first black man to earn a doctorate from Harvard University.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] In 2005, Morris and a group of peers persuaded the American Sociological Association to rename their top award after Du Bois.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] In his 2015 book, *The Scholar Denied: W.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] Du Bois and the Birth of Modern Sociology*, Morris argued that Du Bois was the founder of modern American sociology, and that his contributions to the field were suppressed for decades due to institutional racism.
[src:erving-goffman/aldon-morris] In 2019, Morris was elected as president-elect of the American Sociological Association, and served as the 112th president of the association in 2021.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Portes's work is known for combining theoretically driven questions with original, large-scale longitudinal research.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Wilson he introduced the concept of the ethnic enclave, and he was among the first sociologists to study the informal economy in advanced as well as developing economies.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] His theory of segmented assimilation, developed with Min Zhou, describes the divergent paths of the immigrant second generation and drew on the Children of Immigrants Longitudinal Study that he directed with Rubén G.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He helped establish the study of immigrant transnationalism as a research field and contributed to debates over social capital.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Urbanization and development formed another aspect of his work, from his studies of Latin American cities to his account of Miami's transformation into an emerging global city.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] His work is widely cited in the sub-fields of economic sociology, cultural sociology, and race and ethnicity.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Portes was born in Havana, Cuba, on October 13, 1944.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He began undergraduate studies at the University of Havana in 1959 but, after joining the student opposition to the new revolutionary government led by Fidel Castro, was expelled and granted political asylum in the United States, arriving in Miami in 1960 at the age of 16.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He later stated that he was drawn to sociology by a wish to understand the revolution that had displaced him and his family.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 1963 Portes began studying sociology at the Catholic University of Argentina in Buenos Aires, then returned to the United States and earned a Bachelor of Arts in sociology, *summa cum laude*, from Creighton University in Omaha, Nebraska, in 1965.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He pursued graduate study at the University of Wisconsin–Madison, earning a master's degree in 1967 and a doctorate in 1970, and became a naturalized United States citizen in 1968.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] At Wisconsin he studied under the sociologists William H.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Sewell and Archibald Haller; his doctoral research, on political attitudes in the shanty towns around Santiago, Chile, formed the basis of his first book, *Urban Latin America*, co-authored with John Walton.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] After completing his doctorate, Portes spent a year as an assistant professor of sociology at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign before moving in 1971 to the University of Texas at Austin, where he became a tenured associate professor and associate director of Latin American studies.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] At Texas he began the research on immigration that would become his principal focus, launching a study that compared the experiences of Cuban and Mexican immigrants arriving in Texas and Florida.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 1975 Portes joined Duke University as a full professor, combining his work on immigration with research on urbanization and development in Latin America.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] During his years at Duke he spent a year in Brazil as an adviser to the Ford Foundation, studying housing policy in the slums of Rio de Janeiro, and a year as a fellow at the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences at Stanford.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 1980 he moved to Johns Hopkins University, where he held the John Dewey Chair in Arts and Sciences and chaired the sociology department.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] At Hopkins he launched a comparative study of the informal economy, co-editing the resulting volume *The Informal Economy: Studies in Advanced and Less Developed Countries* (1989) with Manuel Castells and Lauren A.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He also led a comparative study of Caribbean urbanization, published as the edited volume *The Urban Caribbean: Transition to the New Global Economy* (1997), with Carlos Dore-Cabral and Patricia Landolt.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In addition, he studied the transformation of Miami in *City on the Edge* (1993), written with Alex Stepick.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Portes joined Princeton University in 1997 as the Howard Harrison and Gabrielle Snyder Beck Professor of Sociology, a chair he held until becoming emeritus in 2014.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 1998 he co-founded the Center for Migration and Development with Marta Tienda, serving as its director from 1999 to 2012.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] His research on the immigrant second generation spanned both appointments, beginning at Johns Hopkins, where he developed the theory of segmented assimilation and launched the Children of Immigrants Longitudinal Study with Rubén G.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Rumbaut, and continuing at Princeton, where it culminated in *Legacies: The Story of the Immigrant Second Generation* (2001).
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Since 2011 Portes has been affiliated with the University of Miami, where he has held the Emilio Bacardi distinguished professorship and serves as a research professor of law and distinguished scholar in the arts and sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In this later period he returned to the study of Miami, publishing *The Global Edge* (2018) and *Emerging Global Cities* (2022) with Ariel C.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He has also served on the board of trustees and the Scientific Council of the IMDEA Social Sciences Institute in Madrid.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Portes's research centers on economic sociology and the sociology of immigration.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] His early immigration research grew out of a long-term study, begun while he was at Texas, that interviewed Cuban and Mexican immigrants on their arrival in the United States and followed them over the next several years.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Wilson, he developed the concept of the ethnic enclave, describing how Cuban exiles in Miami built dense entrepreneurial communities that employed fellow immigrants and offered a path to economic mobility outside the mainstream economy.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] An article he wrote with Saskia Sassen helped establish the subject within the discipline, and the work grew into a five-year, multi-country project published as *The Informal Economy: Studies in Advanced and Less Developed Countries* (1989).
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Rumbaut launched the Children of Immigrants Longitudinal Study, which surveyed several thousand children of immigrants in the Miami and San Diego areas and followed them into early adulthood.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] The study's findings appeared in *Legacies: The Story of the Immigrant Second Generation* (2001), written with Rumbaut.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He later extended the research to Spain through the Longitudinal Study of the Second Generation (ILSEG), conducted with Rosa Aparicio.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] After moving to Princeton, Portes turned to immigrant transnationalism, the cross-border economic, political, and cultural ties that immigrants sustain between their countries of origin and settlement.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He helped define it as a field of study, distinguishing durable transnational activities from occasional cross-border contacts and calling for systematic, comparative research.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Much of this work drew on studies of Colombian, Dominican, and Salvadoran immigrant communities.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Portes was also a contributor to economic sociology and to debates over social capital.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In a widely cited 1998 review he traced the concept's intellectual origins and cautioned against treating it as an unqualified good, separating its sources from its effects.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He brought this work together in *Economic Sociology: A Systematic Inquiry* (2010).
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Throughout his career Portes also studied urbanization and development in Latin America and the United States.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] His early work examined politics and poverty in Latin American cities, from the shanty towns of Santiago to the favelas of Rio de Janeiro, and he later directed comparative studies of Caribbean urbanization.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In *City on the Edge* (1993) he analyzed how immigration, and the Cuban enclave in particular, reshaped Miami into a multicultural metropolis.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] He returned to the city decades later, developing with Ariel C.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Armony a comparative account of how Miami and comparable cities emerge as global cities.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Portes was elected a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1998 and a member of the National Academy of Sciences in 2001, and he is a member of the American Philosophical Society and the National Academy of Education.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] His book *City on the Edge: The Transformation of Miami* (1993), co-authored with Alex Stepick, won the Robert E.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Park Award for best book in urban sociology from the American Sociological Association (ASA) in 1995 and the Anthony Leeds Award for best book in urban anthropology.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 2002 his *Legacies: The Story of the Immigrant Second Generation* received both the Distinguished Scholarly Publication Award and the W.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] Thomas and Florian Znaniecki Award also from the ASA.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 2008 he received the NAS Award for Scientific Reviewing from the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/alejandro-portes] In 2019 Portes received the Princess of Asturias Award in the social sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] He earned a B.A. from Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, in 1979, having created his interdisciplinary course of study, and an M.A. in the social sciences from the University of Chicago in Illinois in 1980.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] He lives in the Boston area and works as an independent scholar, writing books about research in the areas of education, parenting, and human behavior.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Kohn's ideas on education have been influenced by the works of John Dewey and Jean Piaget.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Kohn has been critical of several aspects of traditional schooling.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Classroom management and discipline are, in his view, focused more on eliciting compliance than on helping students become caring, responsible problem-solvers.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] While *Unconditional Parenting* (2005) is Kohn's first book that deals primarily with raising children, he devoted two chapters to this topic in *Punished by Rewards* (1993).
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] He discusses the need for parents to remember their long-term goals for their children, such as helping them grow into responsible and caring people, rather than short-term goals, such as obedience.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Later, he expanded this critique to suggest that positive reinforcement, like certain forms of punitive "consequences," amounts to forms of conditional parenting, in which love is made contingent on pleasing or obeying the parent.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Two of Kohn's books, *No Contest* (1986) and *Punished by Rewards* (1993), address competition and "pop behaviorism" in workplaces as well as in families and schools.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Both attracted considerable attention in business circles, particularly when the late W.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Edwards Deming, known for inspiring the quality improvement movement in organizations, endorsed both books.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Kohn spoke at conferences and individual corporations on management during the 1990s, and his work was debated in the *Harvard Business Review*, *CFO Magazine*, the *American Compensation Association Journal*, and other publications.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] This includes eight issues in education (e.g., homework, standardized testing, grades, teaching styles), two on parenting, and four on general topics (e.g. human nature, competition, motivation).
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] His books have been translated into two dozen languages.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Kohn has written articles for academic journals, magazines and newspapers.
[src:erving-goffman/alfie-kohn] Among the publications to which he has contributed are *The Atlantic*, *The New York Times*, *Harvard Business Review*, *The Chronicle of Higher Education*, and *Parents*.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 2007, *The Times Higher Education Guide* listed him as the sixth most-cited author of books in the humanities and social sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman was the 73rd president of the American Sociological Association.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His best-known contribution to social theory is his study of symbolic interaction.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This took the form of dramaturgical analysis, beginning with his 1956 book *The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life*.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His major areas of study included the sociology of everyday life, social interaction, the social construction of self, social organization (framing) of experience, and particular elements of social life such as total institutions and stigmas.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman was born 11 June 1922, in Mannville, Alberta, Canada, to Max Goffman and Anne Goffman, née Averbach.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He was from a family of Ukrainian Jews who had emigrated to Canada at the turn of the nineteenth century.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He had an older sister, Frances Bay, who became an actress.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The family moved to Dauphin, Manitoba, where his father operated a successful tailoring business.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] John's Technical High School in Winnipeg, where his family had moved that year.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1939, he enrolled at the University of Manitoba, majoring in chemistry.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He interrupted his studies and moved to Ottawa to work in the film industry for the National Film Board of Canada, established by John Grierson.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Later he developed an interest in sociology.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Also during this time, he met the renowned North American sociologist Dennis Wrong.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Their meeting motivated Goffman to leave the University of Manitoba and enroll at the University of Toronto, where he studied under C.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Hart and Ray Birdwhistell, graduating in 1945 with a BA in sociology and anthropology.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Later he moved to the University of Chicago, where he received an MA (1949) and PhD (1953) in sociology.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] For his doctoral dissertation, from December 1949 to May 1951 he lived and collected ethnographic data on the island of Unst in the Shetland Islands.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's dissertation, entitled *Communication Conduct in an Island Community* (1953), was completed under the supervision of W.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Lloyd Warner, Donald Horton, and Anselm Strauss.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The research Goffman did on Unst inspired him to write his first major work, *The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life* (1956).
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] After graduating from the University of Chicago, in 1954–1957 he was an assistant to the athletic director at the National Institute for Mental Health in Bethesda, Maryland.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Participant observation done there led to his essays on mental illness and total institutions which came to form his second book, *Asylums: Essays on the Social Situation of Mental Patients and Other Inmates* (1961).
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1958, Goffman became a faculty member in the sociology department at the University of California, Berkeley, first as a visiting professor, then from 1962 as a full professor.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1968, he moved to the University of Pennsylvania, receiving the Benjamin Franklin Chair in Sociology and Anthropology, due largely to the efforts of Dell Hymes, a former colleague at Berkeley.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1969, he became a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1970, Goffman became a cofounder of the American Association for the Abolition of Involuntary Mental Hospitalization and coauthored its Platform Statement.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1971, he published *Relations in Public*, in which he tied together many of his ideas about everyday life, seen from a sociological perspective.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Another major book of his, *Frame Analysis*, came out in 1974.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He received a Guggenheim Fellowship for 1977–1978.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1979, Goffman received the Cooley-Mead Award for Distinguished Scholarship, from the Section on Social Psychology of the American Sociological Association.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He was elected the 73rd president of the American Sociological Association, serving in 1981–1982, but was unable to deliver the presidential address in person due to progressing illness.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Posthumously, in 1983, Goffman received the Mead Award from the Society for the Study of Symbolic Interaction.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1952, Goffman married Angelica Schuyler Choate (nicknamed Sky); in 1953, their son Thomas was born.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Angelica experienced mental illness and died by suicide in 1964.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 1981, Goffman married sociolinguist Gillian Sankoff.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The following year, their daughter Alice was born.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Outside his academic career, Goffman was known for his interest, and relative success, in the stock market and gambling.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] At one point, in pursuit of his hobbies and ethnographic studies, he became a pit boss at a Las Vegas casino.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman died in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on 19 November 1982, of stomach cancer.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman was influenced by Herbert Blumer, Émile Durkheim, Sigmund Freud, Everett Hughes, Alfred Radcliffe-Brown, Talcott Parsons, Alfred Schütz, Georg Simmel, and W.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Hughes was the "most influential of his teachers" according to Tom Burns.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Gary Alan Fine and Philip Manning have said that Goffman never engaged in serious dialogue with other theorists, but his work has influenced and been discussed by numerous contemporary sociologists, including Anthony Giddens, Jürgen Habermas, and Pierre Bourdieu.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Though Goffman is often associated with the symbolic interaction school of sociological thought, he did not see himself as a representative of it, and so Fine and Manning conclude that he "does not easily fit within a specific school of sociological thought".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His ideas are also "difficult to reduce to a number of key themes"; his work can be broadly described as developing "a comparative, qualitative sociology that aimed to produce generalizations about human behavior".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman made substantial advances in the study of face-to-face interaction, elaborated the "dramaturgical approach" to human interaction, and developed numerous concepts that have had a massive influence, particularly in the field of the micro-sociology of everyday life.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Much of his work was about the organization of everyday behavior, a concept he termed "interaction order".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He contributed to the sociological concept of framing (frame analysis), to game theory (the concept of strategic interaction), and to the study of interactions and linguistics.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] With regard to the latter, he argued that the activity of speaking must be seen as a social rather than a linguistic construct.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] From a methodological perspective, Goffman often employed qualitative approaches, specifically ethnography, most famously in his study of social aspects of mental illness, in particular the functioning of total institutions.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Overall, his contributions are valued as an attempt to create a theory that bridges the agency-and-structure divide—for popularizing social constructionism, symbolic interaction, conversation analysis, ethnographic studies, and the study and importance of individual interactions.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His influence extended far beyond sociology: for example, his work provided the assumptions of much current research in language and social interaction within the discipline of communication.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman introduced the concept of nonperson treatment as a level of social interaction.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman defined "impression management" as a person's attempts to present an acceptable image to those around them, verbally or nonverbally.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This definition is based on Goffman's idea that people see themselves as others view them, so they attempt to see themselves as if they are outside looking in.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman broke from George Herbert Mead and Herbert Blumer in that while he did not reject the way people perceive themselves, he was more interested in the actual physical proximity or the "interaction order" that molds the self.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In other words, Goffman believed that impression management can be achieved only if the audience is in sync with a person's self-perception.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] If the audience disagrees with the image someone is presenting then their self-presentation is interrupted.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] People present images of themselves based on how society thinks they should act in a particular situation.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This decision how to act is based on the concept of definition of the situation.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Definitions are all predetermined and people choose how they will act by choosing the proper behavior for the situation they are in.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman also draws from William Thomas for this concept.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Thomas believed that people are born into a particular social class and that the definitions of the situations they will encounter have already been defined for them.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] For instance. when an individual from an upper-class background goes to a black-tie affair, the definition of the situation is that they must mind their manners and act according to their class.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In 2007, *The Times Higher Education Guide* listed Goffman as the sixth most-cited author in the humanities and social sciences, behind Michel Foucault, Pierre Bourdieu, and Anthony Giddens, and ahead of Jürgen Habermas.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His popularity with the general public has been attributed to his writing style, described as "sardonic, satiric, jokey", and as "ironic and self-consciously literary", and to its being more accessible than that of most academics.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His style has also been influential in academia, and is credited with popularizing a less formal style in academic publications.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His students included Sherri Cavan, Carol Brooks Gardner, Charles Goodwin, Marjorie Harness Goodwin, John Lofland, Gary T.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Marx, Harvey Sacks, Emanuel Schegloff, David Sudnow, and Eviatar Zerubavel.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Despite his influence, according to Fine and Manning there are "remarkably few scholars who are continuing his work", nor has there been a "Goffman school"; thus his impact on social theory has been simultaneously "great and modest".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Fine and Manning attribute the lack of subsequent Goffman-style research and writing to the nature of his style, which they consider very difficult to duplicate (even "mimic-proof"), and also to his subjects' not being widely valued in the social sciences.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Of his subjects, Fine and Manning observe that the topic of behavior in public places is often stigmatized as trivial and unworthy of serious scholarly attention.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Nonetheless, Fine and Manning note that Goffman is "the most influential American sociologist of the twentieth century".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Elliott and Turner see him as "a revered figure—an outlaw theorist who came to exemplify the best of the sociological imagination", and "perhaps the first postmodern sociological theorist".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's early works consist of his graduate writings of 1949–1953.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His master's thesis was a survey of audience responses to a radio soap opera, *Big Sister*.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] One of its most important elements was a critique of his research methodology—of experimental logic and of variable analysis.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Other writings from the period include *Symbols of Class Status* (1951) and *On Cooling the Mark Out* (1952).
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] His doctoral dissertation, *Communication Conduct in an Island Community* (1953), presented a model of communication strategies in face-to-face interaction, and focused on how everyday rituals affect public projections of self.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's *The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life* was published in 1956, with a revised edition in 1959.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He had developed the book's core ideas from his doctoral dissertation.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] It was Goffman's first and most famous book, for which he received the American Sociological Association's 1961 MacIver Award.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman describes the theatrical performances that occur in face-to-face interactions.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He holds that when someone comes in contact with another person, he attempts to control or guide the impression the other person will form of him, by altering his own setting, appearance and manner.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] At the same time, the second person attempts to form an impression of, and obtain information about, the first person.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman also believes that participants in social interactions engage in certain practices to avoid embarrassing themselves or others.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Society is not homogeneous; we must act differently in different settings.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This recognition led Goffman to his dramaturgical analysis.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He saw a connection between the kinds of "acts" that people put on in their daily lives and theatrical performances.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In a social interaction, as in a theatrical performance, there is an onstage area where actors (people) appear before the audience; this is where positive self-concepts and desired impressions are offered.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] But there is also a backstage—a hidden, private area where people can be themselves and drop their societal roles and identities.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman is sometimes credited with having coined the term "total institution", though Fine and Manning note that he had heard it in lectures by Everett Hughes in reference to any institution in which people are treated alike and in which behavior is regulated.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Regardless of whether Goffman coined the term, he popularized it with his 1961 book *Asylums: Essays on the Social Situation of Mental Patients and Other Inmates*.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The book has been described as "ethnography of the concept of the total institution".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] It was one of the first sociological examinations of the social situation of mental patients in psychiatric hospitals and a major contribution to understanding of social aspects of mental illness.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The first three focus on the experiences of patients; the last, on professional-client interactions.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman is mainly concerned with the details of psychiatric hospitalization and the nature and effects of the process he calls "institutionalization".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He describes how institutionalization socializes people into the role of a good patient, someone "dull, harmless and inconspicuous"—a condition that in turn reinforces notions of chronicity in severe mental illness.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Total institutions greatly affect people's interactions; yet even in such places, people find ways to redefine their roles and reclaim their identities.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In *Behavior in Public Places* (1963), Goffman again focuses on everyday public interactions.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He draws distinctions between several types of public gatherings ("gatherings", "situations", "social occasions") and types of audiences (acquainted versus unacquainted).
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's book *Stigma: Notes on the Management of Spoiled Identity* (1963) examines how, to protect their identities when they depart from approved standards of behavior or appearance, people manage impressions of themselves, mainly through concealment.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Stigma pertains to the shame a person may feel when he or she fails to meet other people's standards, and to the fear of being discredited—which causes the person not to reveal his or her shortcomings.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Thus a person with a criminal record may simply withhold that information for fear of judgment by whoever that person happens to encounter.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's *Interaction Ritual: Essays on Face-to-Face Behavior* is a collection of six essays.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The first four were originally published in the 1950s, the fifth in 1964, and the last was written for the collection.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] They include "On Face-work" (1955); "The Nature of Deference and Demeanor" (1956); "Embarrassment and Social Organization" (1956); "Alienation from Interaction" (1957); "Mental Symptoms and Public Order" (1964); and "Where the Action Is".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He argues that many aspects of everyday social interaction, such as greetings, function as small ritual acts through which individuals reaffirm their social identities and demonstrate their competence.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This perspective is largely influenced by Durkheim.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The first essay, "On Face-work", discusses the concept of face, which is the positive self-image a person holds when interacting with others.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman believes that face "as a sociological construct of interaction is neither inherent in nor a permanent aspect of the person".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Once someone offers a positive self-image of him- or herself to others, they feel a need to maintain and live up to that image.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Inconsistency in how a person projects him- or herself in society risks embarrassment and discredit.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] So people remain guarded to ensure that they do not show themselves to others in an unfavorable light.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's book *Strategic Interaction* (1969) is his contribution to game theory.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] It discusses the compatibility of game theory with the legacy of the Chicago School of sociology and with the perspective of symbolic interactionism.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] It is one of his few works that clearly engage with that perspective.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's view on game theory was shaped by the works of Thomas Schelling.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman presents reality as a form of game, and discusses its rules and the various moves that players can make (the "unwitting", the "naive", the "covering", the "uncovering", and the "counter-uncovering") while trying to get or hide an information.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman credited Gregory Bateson for creating the idea of framing and psychological frames.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] *Frame Analysis: An Essay on the Organization of Experience* (1974) is Goffman's attempt to explain how conceptual frames – ways to organize experience – structure an individual's perception of society.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This book is thus about the organization of experience rather than the organization of society.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] A frame is a set of concepts and theoretical perspectives that organize experiences and guide the actions of individuals, groups and societies.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Frame analysis, then, is the study of the organization of social experience.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] To illustrate the concept of the frame, Goffman gives the example of a picture frame: a person uses the frame (which represents structure) to hold together his picture (which represents the content) of what he is experiencing in his life.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The most basic frames are called primary frameworks.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] A primary framework takes an individual's experience or an aspect of a scene that would originally be meaningless and makes it meaningful.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] One type of primary framework is a natural framework, which identifies situations in the natural world and is completely biophysical, with no human influences.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The other type of framework is a social framework, which explains events and connects them to humans.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] An example of a natural framework is the weather, and an example of a social framework is a meteorologist who predicts the weather.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Focusing on the social frameworks, Goffman seeks to "construct a general statement regarding the structure, or form, of experiences individuals have at any moment of their social life".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman saw this book as his *magnum opus*, but it was not as popular as his earlier works.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In *Frame Analysis*, Erving Goffman provides a platform for understanding and interpreting the interaction between individuals engaging speech communication.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In the chapter "The Frame Analyses of Talk," the focus is put on how words are exchanged and what is being said, specifically in informal talk or conversation.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The concept of framing is introduced through an exploration of why misunderstandings occur in these basic, everyday conversations.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He argues that they are more errors in verbal framing than anything else.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman's key idea is that most conversation is simply a replaying of a strip – what he describes as a personal experience or event.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] When we talk with others, the speaker's goal is often always the same, to provide "evidence for the fairness or unfairness of his current situation and other grounds for sympathy, approval, exoneration, understanding, or amusement.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] And what his listeners are primarily obliged to do is to show some kind of audience appreciation." Essentially, through interaction, we are only looking to be heard, not inspire any kind of action but simply to know that someone listened and understood.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] This is why often a simple head nod or grunt is accepted as an appropriate response in conversation.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman explains that the way a conversation is keyed is critical to understanding the intent behind many utterances in everyday speech.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Key is probably best understood as the tone of the dialogue which can change numerous times during an interaction.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Folklorist Richard Bauman builds heavily on Goffman's work, specifically on the idea of key, in his work pertaining to an analysis of the performance frame.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Bauman details that a performance is dependent on it being properly keyed, without this, the display will not be successful.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Context is one other element to framing that is essential.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] An awareness of these social framings is critical, just as is an awareness of the audience.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Depending on who you're speaking with (a teacher, a child, a loved one, a friend, a pet, etc.) you will curve your speech to fit the frame of what your intended audience is expecting.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman uses the metaphor of conversation being a stage play.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] A play's tone will shift throughout the performance due to the actions taken by the actors; this is similar to how a discussion is keyed – based on what either person says or does over the course of an interaction, the key will change accordingly.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Goffman also claims that a speaker details a drama more often than they provide information.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] They invite the listener to empathize and, as was explained above, they are often not meant to be stirred to take action, but rather to show appreciation; during a play this generally takes the form of applause.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Other similarities include engaging in the suspense the speaker is attempting to create.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In both scenarios, you must put aside the knowledge that the performers know the outcome of the event being relayed and, in a sense, play along.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] All of these things work in concert to provide a foundation of how talk is framed.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In *Gender Advertisements*, Goffman analyzes how gender is represented in the advertising to which all individuals are commonly exposed.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] He suggested that women were often portrayed as passive, dependent on men, and somewhat childlike.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] However, the specific details of his argument remain somewhat ambiguous.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Some scholars interpret his work as an analysis of gender representations in advertising, while others believe that advertisements were simply a convenient—though arguably weak—source of data for examining broader social norms and embodied practices.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Despite this, his book has gained significance as a foundational text influencing more recent cultural studies approaches to media imagery, particularly those focusing on representations of the body.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] She also noted that feminist scholars like Jean Kilbourne "[built] their highly persuasive and widely circulated findings on the nature of gender in advertising on Goffman's original categories".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Each essay addresses both verbal and non-verbal communication through a sociolinguistic model.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The book provides a comprehensive overview of the study of talk.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] In the introduction, Goffman identifies three themes that recur throughout the text: "ritualization, participation framework, and embedding".
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The first essay, "Replies and Responses", concerns "conversational dialogue" and the way people respond during a conversation, both verbally and non-verbally.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The second essay, "Response Cries", considers the use of utterances and their social implications in different social contexts.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Specifically, Goffman discusses "self-talk" (talking to no one in particular) and its role in social situations.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Next, in "Footing", Goffman addresses the way that footing, or alignment, can shift during a conversation.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] The fourth essay, "The Lecture", originally an oral presentation, describes different types and methods of lecture.
[src:erving-goffman/erving-goffman] Lastly, in "Radio Talk", Goffman describes the types and forms of talk used in radio programming and the effect they have on listeners.
